<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="43" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="43">
<taxonomicName authority="Haliday, 1833" authorityName="Haliday" authorityYear="1833" class="Insecta" family="Mymaridae" genus="Anaphes" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Anaphes" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Anaphes Haliday, 1833</taxonomicName>
Extensive synonymy given in Huber (1992).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="43" type="type species">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="43">Type species.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="43">
A formal decision by ICZN on the correct type species to use is pending so the species in not named here. See petition by 
<bibRefCitation author="Huber, JT" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of Zoological Nomenclature" pageId="10" pageNumber="49" pagination="122 - 126" title="Case 3554. Anaphes Haliday, 1833 (Insecta, Hymenoptera): proposed designation of A. fuscipennis Haliday, 1833 as the type species." url="https://doi.org/10.21805/bzn.v68i2.a13" volume="68" year="2011">Huber et al. (2011)</bibRefCitation>
and comments and corrigendum (
<bibRefCitation author="Huber, JT" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of Zoological Nomenclature" pageId="10" pageNumber="49" pagination="132 - 133" title="Comment on Anaphes Haliday 1833 (Insecta, Hymenoptera): proposed designation of A. fuscipennis Haliday, 1833 as the type species." volume="71" year="2014">Huber 2014</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="43">
The worldwide genus 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Mymaridae" genus="Anaphes" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Anaphes" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Anaphes</taxonomicName>
contains a variety of species known as parasitoids of several insect orders, summarized in 
<bibRefCitation author="Huber, JT" journalOrPublisher="Entomography" pageId="10" pageNumber="49" pagination="185 - 243" title="Systematics, biology, and hosts of the Mymaridae and Mymarommatidae (Insecta: Hymenoptera): 1758 - 1984." volume="4" year="1986">Huber (1986)</bibRefCitation>
. Features that define 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Mymaridae" genus="Anaphes" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Anaphes" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Anaphes</taxonomicName>
include: fore wing with socketed seta present at apex of frenal fold; propodeum with a median longitudinal groove; petiole short, almost vertical, much wider than long crescent closely appressed to gt1; and gt1 longitudinally divided medially.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
